{{- /*
headless-guard.sh.tmpl — skip the whole script on headless/server installs,
resolved from the fact registry.

Everything gated behind this configures a graphical desktop (desktop firewalld
zones, zram-swap disable, ThinkPad ACPI, DNS/NetworkManager reloads, …), none of
which belongs on a headless server (Ubuntu Server, RHEL server, minimal cloud
image, …).

`headless` is a named host fact (.chezmoidata/facts.yaml), probed once per
chezmoi command by write_facts_cache in .install-prerequisites.sh and baked in
below by facts-sh.tmpl. The probe is unchanged, only relocated: the canonical
systemd signal for "graphical workstation vs headless server" is the default boot
target (desktops default to graphical.target, server installs to
multi-user.target), so the host is headless when its default target is not
graphical.target AND no display-manager is enabled —
/etc/systemd/system/display-manager.service is the alias symlink systemd creates
when a DM (gdm/sddm/plasmalogin/…) is enabled, a reliable positive desktop
signal. (`systemctl list-unit-files display-manager.service` is NOT usable: it
exits 0 even when nothing matches.) A host with no systemd resolves the fact
FALSE — treated as a desktop and configured — exactly as the old inline
`command -v systemctl` fall-through did.

INSTALL_SYSTEM_CONFIG_FORCE=1 still overrides, and still layers ON TOP of the
fact rather than inside it — the same shape the installers' FORCE_* use (KTD9).
The registry stays a statement about the HOST; an override is a statement about
the RUN, and the two must not be conflated in facts-sh.tmpl, which
install-system-10-files also consumes for its /etc gates. Note chezmoi records a
clean exit-0 skip as a successful run, so re-run with `chezmoi apply --force`.

The skip MESSAGE is the pre-registry one minus one detail: it used to interpolate
the probe's own `systemctl get-default` output (`default target=%s`). There is no
probe here to interpolate, so the parenthetical states what the fact means
instead. The two override lines are verbatim.

ARGUMENT — a dict, NOT the bare display-name string this partial used to take:

  {{ includeTemplate "headless-guard.sh.tmpl" (dict "ctx" . "name" "my-script") }}

facts-sh.tmpl needs the chezmoi context (.chezmoi.*, .factRegistry), and a
partial's `.` is only ever what its caller passed: there is no route back to the
root context from inside one — chezmoi exposes no `data` template function, and
`includeTemplate` takes exactly one data argument. So the caller hands over both,
the way fingerprint.tmpl already does. A call site still passing a bare string
aborts the apply with a message naming the fix, rather than rendering a guard
whose FACT_HEADLESS is unset and which would therefore never fire.

Consumers get the WHOLE FACT_* set in scope for free — install-system-10-files
resolves its /etc manifest gates straight out of it. Do NOT inline facts-sh.tmpl
again alongside this guard.
*/ -}}
{{- if not (kindIs "map" .) -}}
{{-   fail (printf "headless-guard.sh.tmpl: expected a dict, got a %s (%v). This guard inlines facts-sh.tmpl, which needs the chezmoi context, so the call site must pass it: {{ includeTemplate \"headless-guard.sh.tmpl\" (dict \"ctx\" . \"name\" %q) }}" (kindOf .) . .) -}}
{{- end -}}
{{- $name := .name -}}
{{ includeTemplate "facts-sh.tmpl" .ctx }}
# Skip on headless / server installs; see .chezmoitemplates/headless-guard.sh.tmpl
# for the full rationale. Override with INSTALL_SYSTEM_CONFIG_FORCE=1 — the
# override is checked FIRST, so it wins over a true headless fact.
if [[ "${INSTALL_SYSTEM_CONFIG_FORCE:-}" != "1" && "$FACT_HEADLESS" -eq 1 ]]; then
  printf '%s: skipped (headless/server install: default target is not graphical.target, no display-manager).\n' '{{ $name }}'
  printf '  Force a run on a server you do want configured with:\n'
  printf '    INSTALL_SYSTEM_CONFIG_FORCE=1 chezmoi apply --force\n'
  exit 0
fi
